The paper deals with the topic of differential privacy, which is a subfield of computer security (cs.CR). It also involves the study of algorithms and their performance, which falls under machine learning (cs.LG). The use of stopping time rules and tracking realized privacy loss suggests a connection to probability and statistics (cs.DS). The paper also discusses the use of privacy parameters, which relates to information theory (cs.IT). Finally, the paper involves the composition of algorithms, which is a topic in theoretical computer science (cs.CC).
